16:51.570 --> 16:56.234
* To lead me
through the night *

16:56.280 --> 16:58.248
* I need someone's arm... *

16:58.280 --> 17:00.578
Damn.

17:00.620 --> 17:02.576
_ Get those
divorce papers yet?

17:05.290 --> 17:08.418
Maybe you played this
all wrong.

17:08.460 --> 17:11.623
I didn't play it right,
that for damn sure.

17:12.730 --> 17:14.129
Damn it!

17:14.160 --> 17:17.425
* I need your love

17:17.470 --> 17:19.563
* So bad...

17:22.370 --> 17:24.429
I told Felix
I would divorce his ass

17:24.470 --> 17:26.506
if he signed
with Milwaukee.

17:26.540 --> 17:28.371
It's like winter eight months
out of the year.

17:28.410 --> 17:30.071
And if you haven't noticed,

17:30.110 --> 17:31.577
there's not a lot
of black folks living there.

17:31.610 --> 17:33.749
Why don't you
convince Felix
to move here?

17:33.780 --> 17:35.611
He and Davis
can play together.

17:35.650 --> 17:36.810
You know they make
a powerful combo.

17:36.850 --> 17:38.249
Well, yeah--

17:38.290 --> 17:39.587
Or are they already
planning that?

17:39.620 --> 17:42.282
It's too early
to talk about it.

17:42.320 --> 17:45.050
Oh, you should talk to Davis.
I'm sure he'll tell you.

17:46.790 --> 17:48.724
( phone line ringing )

17:54.140 --> 17:56.199
- ( cell phone vibrating )
- Sorry, let me grab this.

18:05.880 --> 18:10.146
Oh, my God,
I am so, so, so sorry.

18:10.190 --> 18:12.317
Remy ( over phone ):
So you did stand me up.

18:12.350 --> 18:13.886
Not really.

18:13.920 --> 18:16.286
Okay, so you're
on your way?

18:16.320 --> 18:17.457
No.

18:17.490 --> 18:19.219
Then you stood me up.

18:19.260 --> 18:22.320
And let me_
tell you something,

18:22.360 --> 18:25.158
I'm looking pretty fine,
if I do say so myself.

18:25.200 --> 18:27.760
I know you are.

18:27.800 --> 18:29.768
( laughter, chatter)

18:29.800 --> 18:32.860
Wait, wait, wait,
are you out on our date
without me?

18:32.910 --> 18:34.537
No, no. I--

18:34.580 --> 18:36.901
I had to meet a friend
who flew into town,

18:36.940 --> 18:39.579
and I spaced...

18:39.610 --> 18:42.443
I will make it up to you,
I promise.

18:43.690 --> 18:44.918
You better.

18:44.950 --> 18:46.611
Okay. I got to go.

18:46.650 --> 18:47.787
I'll call you soon.

18:47.820 --> 18:49.515
Bye.

18:49.560 --> 18:50.720
( phone beeps off)

18:53.500 --> 18:54.819
( sighs )

19:04.470 --> 19:07.177
Sorry. ForgotI had
other plans tonight.

19:07.210 --> 19:08.632
A date?

19:10.550 --> 19:13.713
You and Davis
were the perfect couple.

19:13.750 --> 19:16.344
Honestly,
like a fairy tale.

19:16.380 --> 19:18.314
Isn't there some way
you two can work it out?

19:18.350 --> 19:20.454
I know too much now.

19:20.490 --> 19:22.958
I mean, don't you?

19:22.990 --> 19:24.685
How could you go back
to Felix?

19:24.730 --> 19:28.222
What do you mean?

19:28.260 --> 19:32.367
Wait, didn't Felix
ever tell you what
happened that night?

19:34.470 --> 19:36.665
She was a prostitute
that extorted money from us?

19:36.700 --> 19:39.407
So you never
met with her?

19:40.780 --> 19:42.475
Milena Galoudian?

19:42.510 --> 19:45.399
No, just paid her off
like you.

19:46.780 --> 19:48.338
No.

19:48.380 --> 19:50.541
I met with her.

19:50.590 --> 19:53.718
So, do you know
what happened that night?

19:55.290 --> 19:56.848
Just the truth.

20:03.930 --> 20:05.727
You're going to convince Felix

20:05.770 --> 20:07.397
to withdraw from
the New York deal.

20:07.440 --> 20:09.635
- What?
- I don't want Davis up there.

20:09.670 --> 20:11.399
I want him here,
close to Micah.

20:11.440 --> 20:13.431
You refuse to go to Milwaukee.

20:13.480 --> 20:15.505
You want to be here,
close to family.

20:15.540 --> 20:17.872
Your sister and your friends.

20:17.910 --> 20:19.502
Me.

20:19.550 --> 20:21.916
Felix will do what you want.

20:21.950 --> 20:24.418
And this is what
you want.

20:24.450 --> 20:26.247
Are you threatening me?

20:26.290 --> 20:28.508
It's all about spin.

20:28.560 --> 20:30.425
About reputation.

20:30.460 --> 20:33.429
I am not going
to be blackmailed.

20:33.460 --> 20:35.257
( laughs )

20:36.960 --> 20:39.929
If you don't convince Felix
to play in New Orleans,

20:39.970 --> 20:42.359
a tape of Milena Galoudian

20:42.400 --> 20:44.766
re-telling what your husband
did to her that night

20:44.810 --> 20:46.539
will be on every
gossip site

20:46.570 --> 20:49.277
you've ever heard of
by tomorrow.

20:49.310 --> 20:51.904
I guarantee it'll ruin
the Knicks deal.

20:51.950 --> 20:53.975
It'll ruin Felix's career.

20:55.820 --> 20:58.311
And if you're anything
like me,

20:58.350 --> 21:00.238
it'll _ruin
your fairy tale.

21:09.860 --> 21:12.294
I told his cheap ass
I didn't play Double Dutch

21:12.330 --> 21:13.866
when I was a girl,

21:13.900 --> 21:16.892
and I don't pay "Dutch"
now that I'm a woman.

21:16.940 --> 21:18.567
( both laugh )

21:18.610 --> 21:20.532
You should have seen his face.
He was looking stupid.

21:20.580 --> 21:23.378
"Pay Dutch."

21:23.410 --> 21:25.776
Well, I don't pay
my wait staff

21:25.810 --> 21:28.449
to sit around and talk
while they're on the clock.

21:28.480 --> 21:30.983
So, get up
and get on back to work.

21:31.020 --> 21:33.454
Uh, what work?
Ain't nobody in here.

21:33.490 --> 21:35.549
Well, you better find
some work to do,

21:35.590 --> 21:37.956
because _this_ little
open mic night

21:37.990 --> 21:39.628
comedy session
you got going on?

21:39.660 --> 21:40.991
Closed.

21:44.700 --> 21:46.463
You know you need
to get out, girl.

21:46.500 --> 21:49.936
Get your mind
off Hollywood.

21:49.970 --> 21:52.962
Dance a little bit.
Have some fun.

21:53.010 --> 21:54.534
You'll forget
all about him.

21:55.780 --> 21:57.543
Oh, hey, baby.

21:57.580 --> 21:59.673
P_ut those over
in the corner,
thank you.

21:59.710 --> 22:01.814
Of course, miss.
No problem.

22:01.850 --> 22:04.614
Mm, you should come out
with us to the Juke tonight.

22:04.650 --> 22:06.345
The Juke?

22:06.390 --> 22:08.358
What y'all know about that?

22:08.390 --> 22:09.880
We know enough.

22:09.920 --> 22:12.559
What you got to say about it,
Mr. Delivery Man?

22:12.590 --> 22:14.023
My name's Dayo.

22:14.060 --> 22:15.925
Me and a few of my boys
are going to be there.

22:15.960 --> 22:18.360
We going to be there, too.

22:18.400 --> 22:19.719
What?

22:19.770 --> 22:21.931
Well...

22:21.970 --> 22:25.007
I hope you let me
buy you beautiful ladies
a drink then.

22:27.640 --> 22:29.574
He going to buy us drinks.

22:29.610 --> 22:31.339
( laughs )

22:32.650 --> 22:33.639
Girl, get to work.

22:33.680 --> 22:35.011
( singing )
Gonna go party!

22:35.050 --> 22:36.517
( laughs )

22:39.650 --> 22:41.550
- ( knock at door )
- Come on in.

22:41.590 --> 22:45.879
Sorry. Mr. Des Champs?
Nova Bordelon.

22:45.930 --> 22:47.056
"New Orleans Daily News."

22:47.090 --> 22:49.752
Right. Have a seat.

22:49.800 --> 22:51.995
So, you want to know

22:52.030 --> 22:54.965
about the life
of a public defender?

22:55.000 --> 22:56.558
I'm flattered, but--

22:56.600 --> 22:58.568
Actually, I'm here
about something else.

22:58.610 --> 23:01.704
The interview was just a ruse
to get past the guard dogs.

23:01.740 --> 23:03.640
Oh. You can see
I'm busy, so--

23:03.680 --> 23:05.045
I'll be fast.

23:05.080 --> 23:07.412
I'm here about
one of your cases.

23:07.450 --> 23:09.577
It's a kid by the name
of DeVonte Bonclair.

23:09.620 --> 23:11.042
He goes by "Too Sweet."

23:11.090 --> 23:13.558
I was told you were
his assigned defender.

23:13.590 --> 23:15.888
He's been out on bail for
a couple of months, and he
hasn't heard anything back--

23:15.920 --> 23:18.457
No offense, Miss Bordelon,
but I don't have a clue

23:18.490 --> 23:20.185
who you're talking about,
and I'm not going to know,

23:20.230 --> 23:23.529
not until his folder
works its way up that stack,

23:23.570 --> 23:25.526
and that stack over there.

23:25.570 --> 23:27.936
You say that
like it's okay.

23:27.970 --> 23:29.835
Look, this isn't
some law show

23:29.870 --> 23:32.703
where the good guy
represents the innocent kid

23:32.740 --> 23:34.628
and everyone
goes home happy.

23:34.680 --> 23:37.569
In real life
we're so backed up here,

23:37.610 --> 23:39.202
we can't even
represent folks.

23:39.250 --> 23:41.218
We're turning people away.

23:41.250 --> 23:44.742
The cases we_ do have aren't
gang to trial for years.

23:44.790 --> 23:46.712
So this kid is supposed
to just live in limbo?

23:46.750 --> 23:48.479
Don't know if he can
move on with his life

23:48.520 --> 23:50.784
or if he's going to get
thrown back in jail?

23:52.230 --> 23:54.698
Do you know what that does
to a person?

23:54.730 --> 23:57.699
- It's inhumane.
- Absolutely.

23:57.730 --> 24:00.767
We don't have the money
or the manpower
to move faster.

24:00.800 --> 24:04.031
It's like purgatory.
For all of us.

24:07.040 --> 24:08.473
I'm sorry.

24:08.510 --> 24:10.102
So am I.

24:12.210 --> 24:13.677
Hollywood:
And after all these years,

24:13.720 --> 24:14.971
she don't give me
the time of day?

24:15.020 --> 24:16.248
Like I'm somebody
off the street.

24:16.280 --> 24:18.043
No, no, I deserve
better than that.

24:18.090 --> 24:20.081
- You're right about that.
- And I been good to Vi.

24:20.120 --> 24:22.657
Ain't nobody say you ain't,
except Aunt Vi.

24:22.690 --> 24:25.227
- Ain't that the truth.
- I ain't lying.

24:25.260 --> 24:27.023
Darla:
Blue, we've already
read three books.

24:27.060 --> 24:29.494
Blue:
Please, Mommy,
just one more.

24:29.530 --> 24:30.827
Listen to your mom, Blue.

24:30.870 --> 24:33.065
- Blue: But, Pop...
- Go to bed.

24:35.700 --> 24:39.204
Enough about me.
What's up with Darla?

24:39.240 --> 24:40.639
What,
you talking about us?

24:42.280 --> 24:44.771
Nothing.
You know, just...

24:44.810 --> 24:47.643
Mm-mm. Don't give me
that "nothing," now.

24:47.680 --> 24:50.069
I ain't seen you
grin this hard

24:50.120 --> 24:52.611
since hush was a puppy
and tater was a tot.

24:54.790 --> 24:57.281
Things just good.

24:57.320 --> 24:59.925
That's all.

24:59.960 --> 25:01.951
- ( knock on door)
- Boogie: Hey! Hey, I hear you.

25:02.000 --> 25:03.297
- Who that?
- Hollywood: Boogie!

25:03.330 --> 25:04.922
Boogie, come on
in here, boy!

25:04.970 --> 25:07.791
- What do you say, Boogie?
- Hey, Ralph Angel.

25:07.840 --> 25:09.535
H-town.

25:09.570 --> 25:11.606
Y'all know what
Goddamn day it is?

25:11.640 --> 25:13.733
- Friday.
- All right!
So where the party at?

25:13.780 --> 25:14.929
Mm-mm.

25:14.980 --> 25:16.106
Boogie:
Hey, we got to live.

25:16.140 --> 25:17.277
Especially you.

25:17.310 --> 25:18.675
Walking around
with your head all down,

25:18.710 --> 25:20.200
looking like
your dog died.

25:20.250 --> 25:22.138
Because you sad
about Violet?

25:22.180 --> 25:24.045
Come on, man,
let's hit up a place.

25:24.090 --> 25:28.015
I appreciate it, all right?
But today just ain't the day.

25:28.060 --> 25:29.618
You killing me, 'Wood.

25:29.660 --> 25:31.981
I'm going to go check
on Darla and Blue.

25:32.030 --> 25:33.998
'Wood, we going
to do this.

25:34.030 --> 25:35.588
Hollywood:
Oh, we are, huh?

25:35.630 --> 25:36.995
Ralph Angel:
Get your head in the game.

25:37.030 --> 25:40.591
- Talk to him, Boogie.
- All right, man.

25:40.640 --> 25:42.267
- Get your head in the game.
- Hollywood: Mm-mm.

25:42.300 --> 25:44.063
Now, you heard
what he said, now.

25:44.110 --> 25:46.203
Don't be making us look old
in front of young blood.

25:46.240 --> 25:50.131
Old? That's you over there
with that Halloween
candy cane shirt.

25:50.180 --> 25:51.943
( both laugh )

25:51.980 --> 25:54.210
Okay, all right.
So come on, then.

25:54.250 --> 25:56.241
A little bit of fun
ain't never killed nobody.

25:56.280 --> 25:58.680
Right? Just one night.

26:00.150 --> 26:01.617
One night.

26:01.660 --> 26:04.049
( hip-hop music playing )

26:09.030 --> 26:10.998
( indistinct chatter )

26:30.920 --> 26:32.649
Thank you, baby.

26:32.690 --> 26:34.089
( laughs )

26:35.660 --> 26:37.685
All right. So you can't
just stand here.

26:37.730 --> 26:39.220
- Come on.
- Ah.

26:39.260 --> 26:40.659
( laughs )

26:51.010 --> 26:53.808
( indistinct chatter )

26:53.840 --> 26:55.307
That's what
I'm talking about, man.

26:55.340 --> 26:57.103
Hey, all right, man.
I'll grab us some drinks.

26:57.140 --> 26:58.676
- All right.
- All right? I got you.

26:58.710 --> 27:00.200
You know what I'm drinking
though, huh?

27:00.250 --> 27:01.649
Boogie:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I got it.

27:01.680 --> 27:03.910
- He's so excited.
- I know.

27:03.950 --> 27:06.214
( both laugh )

27:06.250 --> 27:08.309
Man, I'm glad
you came out, though.

27:08.360 --> 27:10.828
All right.
I'm doing good, okay?

27:10.860 --> 27:12.179
- Ralph: All right.
- Okay.

27:12.230 --> 27:14.152
Let's see what's happening.

27:21.440 --> 27:22.964
( laughing )

27:26.710 --> 27:28.439
All right, hold up.
Hold up.

27:28.480 --> 27:30.630
You don't want
to do that.

27:39.320 --> 27:41.880
Look, I'm out.

27:41.920 --> 27:43.353
Nah, 'Wood...

27:43.390 --> 27:44.948
You tell Boogie
I bounced.

27:44.990 --> 27:47.288
'Wood, hold up.

27:48.860 --> 27:50.088
Hold...

27:56.140 --> 27:58.768
I didn't know you could
move like that.

27:58.810 --> 28:00.266
Well, now you do, Dayo.

28:00.310 --> 28:01.902
( chuckles )

28:06.250 --> 28:08.115
Yeah.

28:08.150 --> 28:09.879
Night.

28:09.920 --> 28:13.139
Wait, now. The night ain't
got to end like this.

28:13.190 --> 28:15.454
Well, me and Roberta, we--

28:15.490 --> 28:17.355
I got my own ride home, Vi.

28:17.390 --> 28:18.721
See there?

28:18.760 --> 28:20.159
I got music
back at my place.

28:20.190 --> 28:21.999
We could pick up right
where we left off.

28:22.030 --> 28:24.123
I had a really nice night.

28:24.170 --> 28:25.922
( clears throat )

28:25.970 --> 28:29.963
But it's late and I'm going
home, get in bed.

28:30.000 --> 28:32.002
By myself.

28:32.040 --> 28:35.407
And I will see you
the next delivery date.

28:40.350 --> 28:43.239
Good afternoon, Xavier,
and welcome

28:43.280 --> 28:46.215
to our conversation series
on soaal justice.

28:46.250 --> 28:49.356
I'm Melissa Harris-Perry
and joining me on stage today

28:49.390 --> 28:51.221
is Nova Bordelon.

28:51.260 --> 28:54.491
She's an award-winning
investigative reporter

28:54.530 --> 28:56.225
with the
"New Orleans Daily News,"

28:56.260 --> 28:58.091
and my soror.

28:58.130 --> 28:59.222
Welcome.

28:59.270 --> 29:00.862
Thanks for having me.

29:02.870 --> 29:05.805
Now, Nova,
our conversation today
is going to focus on

29:05.840 --> 29:08.206
the idea of the journalist
as activist.

29:08.240 --> 29:09.832
And looking at your body
of work,

29:09.880 --> 29:11.472
of which I'm a big fan,

29:11.510 --> 29:14.115
you've covered everything
from police corruption

29:14.150 --> 29:16.243
in low-income communities,

29:16.280 --> 29:20.239
to the problem of the American
migrant workforce.

29:20.290 --> 29:23.851
When you think of your role
as a journalist,

29:23.890 --> 29:25.983
do you feel a sense
of responsibility

29:26.030 --> 29:28.851
to take an advocacy position
in your work?

29:28.900 --> 29:30.299
I absolutely do.

29:30.330 --> 29:31.968
I've worked hard
to get to a place

29:32.000 --> 29:33.968
where I can choose
the stories I want to cover,

29:34.000 --> 29:36.889
and it's important for me
to reflect humanity in my work.

29:36.940 --> 29:38.828
And so there's definitely
an advocacy component

29:38.870 --> 29:40.406
in everything that I write.

29:40.440 --> 29:43.034
I think it's critical
that you use your platform,

29:43.080 --> 29:44.843
whatever that is--

29:44.880 --> 29:47.405
blogs, Twitter,
social media, whatever--

29:47.450 --> 29:48.917
to empower as well as--

29:50.180 --> 29:51.442
As educate.

29:51.490 --> 29:53.412
( applause )

29:58.030 --> 30:00.123
Let's talk about a piece
you wrote earlier this year,

30:00.160 --> 30:05.291
on the for-profit prison complex
and over-policing.

30:05.330 --> 30:07.161
I understand that you
were able to help
the young man

30:07.200 --> 30:10.169
featured in that story.
His name is Too Sweet.

30:10.200 --> 30:12.202
Yes, that's correct.
He's been released on bail,

30:12.240 --> 30:14.071
but we still have
a huge uphill battle

30:14.110 --> 30:15.407
to get his charges dropped.

30:15.440 --> 30:17.305
The Public Defenders' office
in LOUISlana

30:17.340 --> 30:19.046
is woefully underfunded,

30:19.080 --> 30:21.173
yet they are sure happy to keep
the bail money coming in.

30:21.220 --> 30:23.438
It could be years
before Too Sweet gets a trial.

30:23.480 --> 30:26.313
But I just want to reiterate,
his charges are quite serious.

30:26.350 --> 30:30.081
I mean, intent to distribute,
assault on an officer.

30:30.120 --> 30:32.088
So those are-- Those are
pretty serious charges.

30:32.130 --> 30:33.927
Serious charges
if they were true.

30:33.960 --> 30:37.498
Now, regardless,
no minor should _be held
in an adult prison.

30:37.530 --> 30:39.327
They are not equipped
to handle

30:39.370 --> 30:43.466
the emotional and psychological
trauma of prison culture.

30:43.500 --> 30:46.060
It's a good point.
That's a form of PTSD

30:46.110 --> 30:48.931
- that we rarely talk about.
- Yeah.

30:48.980 --> 30:50.902
Now, I know you're not
publicly affiliated

30:50.950 --> 30:53.339
with the Black Lives Matter
network or movement,

30:53.380 --> 30:55.940
but BLM has really
changed the way

30:55.980 --> 30:59.086
that civil rights and social
justice are articulated,

30:59.120 --> 31:02.351
and the way they're executed
in this country.

31:02.390 --> 31:05.086
But now, with one tweet,
you can move the needle.

31:05.130 --> 31:07.655
So as a journalist,
give me your thoughts

31:07.690 --> 31:11.228
on the Black Lives Matter
movement as a whole.

31:11.270 --> 31:13.966
The BLM energy was formally
birthed in response

31:14.000 --> 31:17.265
to the 2012 acquittal
of Trayvon Martin's killer.

31:17.300 --> 31:19.359
And there have been
chapters around the world

31:19.410 --> 31:21.469
that respond to incidents
of anti-blackness

31:21.510 --> 31:24.206
and state-sanctioned violence
against black people.

31:24.250 --> 31:26.206
The movement is for people
who are interested

31:26.250 --> 31:28.115
in the liberation
of black lives.

31:28.150 --> 31:31.381
And yet there's serious
criticism of BLM.

31:31.420 --> 31:33.240
What do you make
of those critiques,

31:33.290 --> 31:36.157
especially of their
relationship with
law enforcement?

31:36.190 --> 31:39.387
Nova:
The one criticism
that frustrates me the most

31:39.430 --> 31:42.991
is this idea that there's
a need for a leader,

31:43.030 --> 31:45.123
which is this
coded language for--

31:45.170 --> 31:48.560
meaning that there's no
straight male leader
